ter a test. Should I create a more direct test that runs in static? I think the issue might be related to dynamic access in the report, which is only generated during the native image build and not at runtime. This may explain why prior tests showed coverage that doesn't seem consistent. I should inspect the class initialization build arguments to see if any adjustments are needed.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating test coverage for Introspector**\\n\\nI think the dynamic access call in the suite isn’t being covered for the Introspector because it uses the suite(). It seems our testing pattern isn’t sufficient. The existing IntrospectorTestCaseTest covers Method.invoke, but not class$, likely because suite() doesn’t use TestSuite(Class). I'm considering if class$ comes from the constructor instead. However, the Parser suite does use TestSuite(Class), so why is it not covered? Maybe the dynamic access with `Class.forName` is hidden and not tracked. I need to dig deeper!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering parser access**\\n\\nI’m thinking I don’t have a Parser ready, and I maybe need a direct class reference. Should I try using `ParserTestCase.class.getName()` to make it reachable? But will that invoke reflection? It seems like this class literal in test code isn’t tracked. I shouldn’t use direct reflection. The public API could accept `ParserTestCase.class.getName()`, but I'm wondering if the class literal will end up initializing. I’m not sure!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_46bZw2gUieM3n4pZk0CfAXU8|fc_0a577948bf92a7e50169ef814399188196a6b55a8093ad8bd3", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "ls tests/src/velocity/velocity-dep/1.4/build/test-results/test | grep Parser || true; ls tests/src/velocity/velocity-dep/1.4/build/reports/tests/test/classes | grep Parser || true; rg -n \"ParserTestCaseTest|validatesParser\" tests/src/velocity/velocity-dep/1.4/build/test-results tests/src/velocity/velocity-dep/1.4/build/r